#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:4
msgid "Setting up and using your development environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:9
msgid "Recommended development setup"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:11
msgid ""
"Since NumPy contains parts written in C and Cython that need to be compiled "
"before use, make sure you have the necessary compilers and Python "
"development headers installed - see :ref:`building-from-source`. Building "
"NumPy as of version ``1.17`` requires a C99 compliant compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:16
msgid ""
"Having compiled code also means that importing NumPy from the development "
"sources needs some additional steps, which are explained below.  For the "
"rest of this chapter we assume that you have set up your git repo as "
"described in :ref:`using-git`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:23
msgid ""
"If you are having trouble building NumPy from source or setting up your "
"local development environment, you can try to build NumPy with GitHub "
"Codespaces. It allows you to create the correct development environment "
"right in your browser, reducing the need to install local development "
"environments and deal with incompatible dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:29
msgid ""
"If you have good internet connectivity and want a temporary set-up, it is "
"often faster to work on NumPy in a Codespaces environment. For documentation "
"on how to get started with Codespaces, see `the Codespaces docs <https://"
"docs.github.com/en/codespaces>`__. When creating a codespace for the ``numpy/"
"numpy`` repository, the default 2-core machine type works; 4-core will build "
"and work a bit faster (but of course at a cost of halving your number of "
"free usage hours). Once your codespace has started, you can run ``conda "
"activate numpy-dev`` and your development environment is completely set up - "
"you can then follow the relevant parts of the NumPy documentation to build, "
"test, develop, write docs, and contribute to NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:42
msgid "Using virtual environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:44
msgid ""
"A frequently asked question is \"How do I set up a development version of "
"NumPy in parallel to a released version that I use to do my job/research?\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:47
msgid ""
"One simple way to achieve this is to install the released version in site-"
"packages, by using pip or conda for example, and set up the development "
"version in a virtual environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:51
msgid ""
"If you use conda, we recommend creating a separate virtual environment for "
"numpy development using the ``environment.yml`` file in the root of the repo "
"(this will create the environment and install all development dependencies "
"at once)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:56
msgid ""
"$ conda env create -f environment.yml  # `mamba` works too for this command\n"
"$ conda activate numpy-dev"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:59
msgid ""
"If you installed Python some other way than conda, first install "
"`virtualenv`_ (optionally use `virtualenvwrapper`_), then create your "
"virtualenv (named ``numpy-dev`` here) with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:63
msgid "$ virtualenv numpy-dev"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:65
msgid ""
"Now, whenever you want to switch to the virtual environment, you can use the "
"command ``source numpy-dev/bin/activate``, and ``deactivate`` to exit from "
"the virtual environment and back to your previous shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:73
msgid "Testing builds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:75
msgid "Before running the tests, first install the test dependencies::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:77
msgid ""
"$ python -m pip install -r test_requirements.txt\n"
"$ python -m pip install asv # only for running benchmarks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:80
msgid ""
"To build the development version of NumPy and run tests, spawn interactive "
"shells with the Python import paths properly set up etc., use the `spin "
"<https://github.com/scientific-python/spin>`_ utility. To run tests, do one "
"of::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:85
msgid ""
"$ spin test -v\n"
"$ spin test numpy/random  # to run the tests in a specific module\n"
"$ spin test -v -t numpy/core/tests/test_nditer.py::test_iter_c_order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:89
msgid "This builds NumPy first, so the first time it may take a few minutes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:91
msgid ""
"You can also use ``spin bench`` for benchmarking. See ``spin --help`` for "
"more command line options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:96
msgid ""
"If the above commands result in ``RuntimeError: Cannot parse version "
"0+untagged.xxxxx``, run ``git pull upstream main --tags``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:99
msgid ""
"Additional arguments may be forwarded to ``pytest`` by passing the extra "
"arguments after a bare ``--``. For example, to run a test method with the "
"``--pdb`` flag forwarded to the target, run the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:103
msgid "$ spin test -t numpy/tests/test_scripts.py::test_f2py -- --pdb"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:105
msgid ""
"You can also  `match test names using python operators`_ by passing the ``-"
"k`` argument to pytest::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:108
msgid ""
"$ spin test -v -t numpy/core/tests/test_multiarray.py -- -k \"MatMul and not "
"vector\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:112
msgid ""
"Remember that all tests of NumPy should pass before committing your changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:116
msgid ""
"Some of the tests in the test suite require a large amount of memory, and "
"are skipped if your system does not have enough."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:126
msgid "Other build options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:128
msgid ""
"For more options including selecting compilers, setting custom compiler "
"flags and controlling parallelism, see :doc:`scipy:building/"
"compilers_and_options` (from the SciPy documentation.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:134
msgid "Running tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:136
msgid ""
"Besides using ``spin``, there are various ways to run the tests.  Inside the "
"interpreter, tests can be run like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:139
msgid ""
">>> np.test()  \n"
">>> np.test('full')   # Also run tests marked as slow\n"
">>> np.test('full', verbose=2)   # Additionally print test name/file\n"
"\n"
"An example of a successful test :\n"
"``4686 passed, 362 skipped, 9 xfailed, 5 warnings in 213.99 seconds``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:146
msgid "Or a similar way from the command line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:148
msgid "$ python -c \"import numpy as np; np.test()\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:150
msgid ""
"Tests can also be run with ``pytest numpy``, however then the NumPy-specific "
"plugin is not found which causes strange side effects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:153
msgid ""
"Running individual test files can be useful; it's much faster than running "
"the whole test suite or that of a whole module (example: ``np.random."
"test()``). This can be done with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:157
msgid "$ python path_to_testfile/test_file.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:159
msgid ""
"That also takes extra arguments, like ``--pdb`` which drops you into the "
"Python debugger when a test fails or an exception is raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:162
msgid ""
"Running tests with `tox`_ is also supported.  For example, to build NumPy "
"and run the test suite with Python 3.9, use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:165
msgid "$ tox -e py39"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:167
msgid "For more extensive information, see :ref:`testing-guidelines`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:169
msgid ""
"Note: do not run the tests from the root directory of your numpy git repo "
"without ``spin``, that will result in strange test errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:173
msgid "Running Linting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:174
msgid "Lint checks can be performed on newly added lines of Python code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:176
msgid "Install all dependent packages using pip::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:178
msgid "$ python -m pip install -r linter_requirements.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:180
msgid "To run lint checks before committing new code, run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:182
msgid "$ python tools/linter.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:184
msgid ""
"To check all changes in newly added Python code of current branch with "
"target branch, run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:186
msgid "$ python tools/linter.py --branch main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:188
msgid ""
"If there are no errors, the script exits with no message. In case of errors, "
"check the error message for details::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:191
msgid ""
"$ python tools/linter.py --branch main\n"
"./numpy/core/tests/test_scalarmath.py:34:5: E303 too many blank lines (3)\n"
"1       E303 too many blank lines (3)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:195
msgid ""
"It is advisable to run lint checks before pushing commits to a remote branch "
"since the linter runs as part of the CI pipeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:198
msgid "For more details on Style Guidelines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:200
msgid "`Python Style Guide`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:201
msgid "`C Style Guide`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:204
msgid "Rebuilding & cleaning the workspace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:206
msgid ""
"Rebuilding NumPy after making changes to compiled code can be done with the "
"same build command as you used previously - only the changed files will be "
"re-built.  Doing a full build, which sometimes is necessary, requires "
"cleaning the workspace first.  The standard way of doing this is (*note: "
"deletes any uncommitted files!*)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:212
msgid "$ git clean -xdf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:214
msgid ""
"When you want to discard all changes and go back to the last commit in the "
"repo, use one of::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:217
msgid ""
"$ git checkout .\n"
"$ git reset --hard"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:224
msgid "Debugging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:226
msgid ""
"Another frequently asked question is \"How do I debug C code inside NumPy?"
"\". First, ensure that you have gdb installed on your system with the Python "
"extensions (often the default on Linux). You can see which version of Python "
"is running inside gdb to verify your setup::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:231
msgid ""
"(gdb) python\n"
">import sys\n"
">print(sys.version_info)\n"
">end\n"
"sys.version_info(major=3, minor=7, micro=0, releaselevel='final', serial=0)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:237
msgid ""
"Most python builds do not include debug symbols and are built with compiler "
"optimizations enabled. To get the best debugging experience using a debug "
"build of Python is encouraged, see :ref:`advanced_debugging`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:241
msgid ""
"Next you need to write a Python script that invokes the C code whose "
"execution you want to debug. For instance ``mytest.py``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:244
msgid ""
"import numpy as np\n"
"x = np.arange(5)\n"
"np.empty_like(x)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:248
msgid "Now, you can run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:250
msgid "$ spin gdb mytest.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:252
msgid "And then in the debugger::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:254
msgid ""
"(gdb) break array_empty_like\n"
"(gdb) run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:257
msgid ""
"The execution will now stop at the corresponding C function and you can step "
"through it as usual. A number of useful Python-specific commands are "
"available. For example to see where in the Python code you are, use ``py-"
"list``, to see the python traceback, use ``py-bt``.  For more details, see "
"`DebuggingWithGdb`_. Here are some commonly used commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:263
msgid "``list``: List specified function or line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:264
msgid "``next``: Step program, proceeding through subroutine calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:265
msgid "``step``: Continue program being debugged, after signal or breakpoint."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:266
msgid "``print``: Print value of expression EXP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:268
msgid ""
"Rich support for Python debugging requires that the ``python-gdb.py`` script "
"distributed with Python is installed in a path where gdb can find it. If you "
"installed your Python build from your system package manager, you likely do "
"not need to manually do anything. However, if you built Python from source, "
"you will likely need to create a ``.gdbinit`` file in your home directory "
"pointing gdb at the location of your Python installation. For example, a "
"version of python installed via `pyenv <https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv>`_ "
"needs a ``.gdbinit`` file with the following contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:277
msgid "add-auto-load-safe-path ~/.pyenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:281
msgid ""
"Building NumPy with a Python built with debug support (on Linux "
"distributions typically packaged as ``python-dbg``) is highly recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:294
msgid "Understanding the code & getting started"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:296
msgid ""
"The best strategy to better understand the code base is to pick something "
"you want to change and start reading the code to figure out how it works. "
"When in doubt, you can ask questions on the mailing list. It is perfectly "
"okay if your pull requests aren't perfect, the community is always happy to "
"help. As a volunteer project, things do sometimes get dropped and it's "
"totally fine to ping us if something has sat without a response for about "
"two to four weeks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:303
msgid ""
"So go ahead and pick something that annoys or confuses you about NumPy, "
"experiment with the code, hang around for discussions or go through the "
"reference documents to try to fix it. Things will fall in place and soon "
"you'll have a pretty good understanding of the project as a whole. Good Luck!"
msgstr ""
